## The 5-Question Framework

| Question | Answer here |
|---|---|
| What do I **track**? | `count` — character frequencies, incremented for `s`, decremented for `t` |
| When do I **keep going**? | Two full passes — one over `s`, one over `t` |
| What happens **each step**? | +1 for each char in `s`, -1 for each char in `t` |
| What are the **edge cases**? | Different lengths → `False` immediately; empty strings → `True` (both empty) |
| What do I **return**? | `True` if all counts are zero, `False` otherwise |

---

## Aha Moment

An anagram is just a frequency-matching problem. Sorting works but is slower than it needs to be. Once you realize "same characters, same counts", a hash map makes it O(n) — increment for one string, decrement for the other, check everything cancelled out.

